'''Lee Bivens''' is an artist, film producer and [[motorcycle racer]].<ref name="amermoto">{{cite journal|date=March 1998|title=Russel Rules|journal=American Motorcyclist|volume=52|issue=3|pages=124|publisher=American Motorcyclist Assoc|issn=0277-9358|accessdate=June 15, 2011|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B_cDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA22 
}}</ref>

==Career==
[[File:Spirit of the Raptor.jpg|thumb|200px|Spirit of the Raptor]]
Lee Bivens became a full-time professional artist at the age of 18 and is realism painter known for "capturing more than the camera's eye in his paintings".<ref name="atlantajournal">{{cite news| title=Artist captures athletes at height of their game|author      = Diane R. Steep| url         = http://artlee.com/intajccsanned1lrg.jpg| newspaper   = The Atlanta Journal| date        = March 10, 1994| accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref> During his 26-year art career, Bivens spent his extra time racing motorcycles and educating himself on the film industry.  Today, Bivens operates an independent film studio, Bivens Studios Inc.  In Sept. 2011, he completed his first feature film, ''Evolution Creek'', and submitted it for consideration to the Sundance Film Festival.  He has also been published in [[Motorcyclist (magazine)|''Motorcyclist'' magazine]] as an expert.<ref>{{cite journal|date=June 2006|title=Triumph's Daytona 675 Works As Good As It Looks|journal=Motorcyclist Magazine|at=49|publisher=Source Interlink Media|accessdate=June 15, 2011|url=http://www.motorcyclistonline.com/features/122_0606_honda_kawasaki_suzuki_triumph_yamaha_middleweight_sportbike_comparison/jim_west.html}}</ref>  Lee is an official [[United States Air Force]] artist and created the "Spirit of the Raptor (F-22)".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afapo.hq.af.mil/Presentation/common/artistsdetail.cfm?Letter=B&value=1570|title=Blivens, Arnold L|publisher=THE UNITED STATES AIR FORCE ART COLLECTION|accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref>

