{{italic title}} [[File:The Painter and His Pug by William Hogarth.jpg|right|250px]] '''''Painter and his Pug''''' is a 1745 [[self-portrait]] created by [[William Hogarth]]. He began the portrait a decade earlier. The portrait was originally created with the intention of Hogarth wearing formal attire, but was changed to the informal attire sometime during the painting process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tate.org.uk/art/artworks/hogarth-the-painter-and-his-pug-n00112|title=The Painter and his Pug, William Hogarth|publisher=[[Tate Britain]]|date=August 2004|accessdate=May 5, 2013}}</ref> He also added his [[Pug]], [[Trump (dog)|Trump]].
In the portrait, Hogarth himself is in a painting as the [[pug]] is alongside him, making the dog "real" as opposed to the created person.<ref>{{cite book|title=Seven Painters Who Changed the Course of Art History|first=Brian Thom McQuade|last=Ma|year=2012|page=120|isbn=9781477227411}}</ref> The dog is indifferent to the painting, to the books and to the painting palette (which shows Hogarth's [[Line of Beauty]]). So the painting seems to be a [[Vanitas]] still life. But, as an ironic disruption, the cloth behind the dog comes out of the painting.
The painting is part of the collections of the Tate Gallery.
